def: A slovenly woman; a slattern; a draggle-tail.
The second Sunday before Lent; -- so called as being about thesixtieth day before Easter.
By experiment; by experience or trial. J. S. Mill.
Not opportune; inconvenient; unseasonable; as, an inopportuneoccurrence, remark, etc.No visit could have been more inopportune. T. Hook.
To remember; to cause to remember; to mention. [Obs.]
In a glum manner; sullenly; moodily.
Having, or acknowledging, no God; without reverence for God;impious; wicked.-- God"less*ly, adv.-- God"less*ness, n.
A man of learning; one versed in literature or science; aperson eminent for acquirements.
Charged with another bearing of the same figure, and of thecolor of the field, so large that only a narrow border of the firstbearing remains visible; -- said of any heraldic bearing. CompareVoided.

A journal bearing, so called because frequently made of brass.A brass is often lined with a softer metal, when the latter isgenerally called a white metal lining. See Axle box, Journal Box, andBearing.
One who practices or advocates strict conformity to law; intheology, one who holds to the law of works. See Legal, 2 (a).
